comments.message: Doesn't this have to be submitted via github?
Yes, but we can review here, in case there is any change needed.
Can we remove orpAtService.h/c altogether since it doesn't seem to be needed anymore?
Can we remove the orpAtService.h/c files altogether since they shouldn't be needed now?
Why is this and the below change required?
It's not needed, the same to the change below. Although, they will be needed when octave needs GNSS. Have removed.

Hi Vincent,

The changes look OK to me - one comment inserted.  I have a couple of questions, though:

Is the atServer API available now on master for HL7802 builds?

Was testing done to ensure that the atServer API behaves the same as the orpAtService shim + atProxy?  In particular, notifications should be tested.  E.g:

AT+ORP="OJ00Pout/json/value"
+ORP: o@01

OK
AT+ORP="HS00Pout/json/value"
+ORP: h@01

OK
<Go to UI and write JSON to this output>

+ORP: c@01T4294967295,Pout/json/value,D{"name":"testJSON", "number":2 }

Thanks,
Ian

Hi Ian,

Tested the two AT command and got expected results:
ati
ati
HL7802

OK
AT+ORP="OJ00Pout/json/value"
+ORP: o@01

OK
AT+ORP="HS00Pout/json/value"
+ORP: h@01

OK

However, for the third test (Go to UI and write JSON to this output), my module is not configured for octave, and I booked a test bed from test bench, but I was not able to connect to the board for this test. I am looking for another way to test it.
Since the same api name is now being used for both RTOS and Linux, this comment can be removed

Hi Vincent,

If your device is not connected to Octave, you could use the following local command instead of pushing from the UI:

AT+ORP="PJ00Pin/json1/value,D{\"name\":\"testJSON\",\"number\":2}"

Thanks,
Ian

Hi Vincent,
Test evidence looks good - thanks.

Thanks Ian, got the expected result as follows:

at
at
OK
AT+ORP="OJ00Pout/json/value"
+ORP: o@01

OK
AT+ORP="HS00Pout/json/value"
+ORP: h@01

OK
AT+ORP="PJ00Pout/json/value,D{\"name\":\"testJSON\",\"number\":2}"
+ORP: p@01

OK
+ORP: c@01T52.562000,Pout/json/value,D{"name":"testJSON","number":2}
at
at
OK
